WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.240
First of all, the idea that we do not use teachers to teach academic content to students

00:08.240 --> 00:13.360
in a teacher in front of a classroom model, and that is something that just feels so hard

00:13.360 --> 00:18.280
for people to get their heads around because we all grew up in that system and we've always

00:18.280 --> 00:25.940
been told like a great teacher is the key to learning something.

00:25.940 --> 00:30.020
Welcome to the future of Education Podcast, hosted by Mackenzie Price.

00:30.020 --> 00:34.820
Mackenzie is the founder of a revolutionary new school model that's disrupting education

00:34.820 --> 00:35.820
through AI.

00:35.820 --> 00:43.860
Join us as we discuss the latest in education innovation.

00:43.860 --> 00:49.460
This next question is from a parent that is super engaged and excited.

00:49.460 --> 00:51.540
The question is, what should I start with?

00:51.540 --> 00:53.540
I have a one-year-old.

00:54.100 --> 01:00.420
All right, mama or daddy of one-year-old, here's the best advice that I can give to you,

01:01.140 --> 01:04.500
play and love and read to your kid like nobody's business.

01:04.500 --> 01:06.100
That is the best thing.

01:06.100 --> 01:13.860
Get your kid out, getting dirty, let him go play in the mud, go explore, go find worms,

01:13.860 --> 01:17.620
go find tadpoles, do all that kind of cool stuff.

01:17.620 --> 01:21.700
I promise you all these AI tools are going to be around in a few years when your kid's

01:21.700 --> 01:26.580
getting a little bit older and you're going to be able to jump on the education train.

01:26.580 --> 01:30.180
But the best thing that you can do with your one-year-old is just love them like crazy,

01:30.180 --> 01:33.300
play with them like crazy, and read to them like crazy.

01:33.940 --> 01:36.340
Ooh, I really love this next question.

01:36.340 --> 01:44.500
What is the first and biggest mindset change that parents and children need to have in our schools?

01:44.500 --> 01:51.140
And here's what I always tell people, as a private school, families will apply for admission,

01:51.140 --> 01:56.660
but we don't actually base our admission on what kind of grades they had or where they scored in

01:56.660 --> 01:59.700
their transcripts or where they already were in their assessments.

02:00.340 --> 02:06.900
Our biggest thing that we focus on is philosophical alignment with our model of education.

02:06.900 --> 02:09.140
And so there's probably two things.

02:09.140 --> 02:14.180
First of all, they have to change their mind around the idea that the best way to learn

02:14.180 --> 02:15.780
is with a teacher in front of a classroom.

02:15.780 --> 02:19.700
And that's hard because we all grew up in that system.

02:19.700 --> 02:23.780
So I think that's kind of the biggest thing is parents need to understand like this is different,

02:23.780 --> 02:24.980
but it works.

02:24.980 --> 02:30.740
Now, the other big mindset change that parents and kids need to get really comfortable with

02:30.740 --> 02:37.140
is all around the idea of failure, that kids can be challenged, they can do hard things,

02:37.140 --> 02:41.140
and they can fail, and they can learn so much from that failure perspective.

02:41.140 --> 02:46.180
It actually ties in with one of our parent tenants, which is support, don't solve.

02:46.180 --> 02:52.020
We tell parents, hey, you can support your kid, but don't go in and solve their challenges for them.

02:52.020 --> 02:56.420
Allow them the opportunity to learn and struggle and fail.

02:56.420 --> 03:00.820
And we even say sometimes cry on their road to success.

03:00.820 --> 03:03.940
I'm going to combine two of these next questions that I got.

03:03.940 --> 03:06.900
The first was, do you have an alpha homeschool program?

03:06.900 --> 03:11.700
And the second was that they are looking for an online alpha based school for performing arts for

03:11.700 --> 03:12.900
their kid.

03:12.900 --> 03:14.340
And here's the good news.

03:14.340 --> 03:17.060
Yes, we do have a homeschool program.

03:17.060 --> 03:18.660
It's called Alpha Anywhere.

03:18.660 --> 03:21.700
It's currently for third grade through eighth grade.

03:21.700 --> 03:26.420
Those grades will be expanding over time, but right now we're at third grade through eighth grade.

03:26.420 --> 03:31.460
And so regarding the performing arts part of it, one of the things that our families in Alpha Anywhere

03:31.460 --> 03:36.980
are absolutely loving is the fact that they can spend two hours getting their academics done

03:36.980 --> 03:39.700
and then spend the rest of the day doing all these other things.

03:39.700 --> 03:43.780
So we have students who are interested in building out businesses.

03:43.780 --> 03:46.660
We've got kids who are doing really hardcore athletics.

03:46.660 --> 03:51.140
We've got kids who are doing performing arts and theater and music.

03:51.140 --> 03:53.220
And they're able to spend their afternoons doing that.

03:53.220 --> 03:56.260
But there's something else that's really exciting that's happening.

03:56.260 --> 04:04.580
In Texas, we are launching a virtual program for students to be able to do our alpha school

04:05.540 --> 04:11.700
either through Texas Sports Academy if your kid is interested in sports or our GT school program,

04:11.700 --> 04:13.860
which is for gifted and talented kids.

04:13.860 --> 04:21.060
And families as part of that program actually get money from the state to put towards the physical

04:21.060 --> 04:26.420
training that their kids are doing or the GT type academic training that they want to do in the

04:26.420 --> 04:27.140
afternoons.

04:27.140 --> 04:30.980
The reason we're able to do that just so you know is because of the school choice

04:31.620 --> 04:33.380
efforts that have happened in Texas.

04:33.380 --> 04:38.100
So we'll be rolling those out to other states that have that school choice opportunity.

04:38.100 --> 04:42.260
If you want more information on alpha anywhere, you go to alpha anywhere dot co.

04:43.780 --> 04:47.700
Oh, this is a great question that I really love to talk about.

04:47.700 --> 04:54.180
A lot of people will say is music like orchestra or band available at an alpha school?

04:54.180 --> 04:55.540
And here's the answer.

04:55.540 --> 05:02.100
Yes, we have so many awesome music opportunities, but they don't look quite like traditional school

05:02.100 --> 05:02.500
looks like.

05:02.500 --> 05:08.820
So for example, we've got kindergarteners who are doing a piano lab workshop where they're

05:08.820 --> 05:14.980
learning piano instruction on a keyboard and then they're creating their own songs and they're

05:14.980 --> 05:18.500
using AI to notate those songs and then perform them.

05:19.060 --> 05:25.380
We did the same thing with a great panel workshop with our fourth and fifth graders too.

05:25.380 --> 05:30.180
That was really fun to see our middle school students have been doing these awesome school of

05:30.180 --> 05:35.700
rock things where they're not only learning how to play musical instruments, writing original

05:35.700 --> 05:39.300
songs, learning how to play together, but then they have to market their band.

05:39.300 --> 05:44.020
They have to create the brand for their band and their hosting events.

05:44.020 --> 05:48.100
So they get to kind of combine some event management and some marketing management

05:48.100 --> 05:49.620
along with what they're doing.

05:49.620 --> 05:52.180
We actually have a student in Scottsdale.

05:52.180 --> 05:53.620
She's 10 years old.

05:53.620 --> 05:57.700
She released her own written song that was produced.

05:57.700 --> 06:00.340
It is called Feet on the Ground.

06:00.340 --> 06:01.700
It's called Feet on the Ground.

06:01.700 --> 06:05.140
It's on Spotify and it's so totally good, you guys.

06:05.140 --> 06:05.700
I'm serious.

06:05.700 --> 06:06.980
Ruby is a little star.

06:06.980 --> 06:12.020
I swear we're going to see her at the Grammys in a couple of years because she is fantastic.

06:12.020 --> 06:16.180
And so our students get a lot of opportunity to try out musical instruments and do things,

06:16.180 --> 06:24.180
but they're not doing traditional orchestra or band that you would see in traditional schools,

06:24.180 --> 06:26.740
but they get a ton of musical stuff.

06:26.740 --> 06:31.940
We've got great acting workshops that our students engage in where they're doing theater

06:31.940 --> 06:32.980
and things like that.

06:32.980 --> 06:38.020
We always tie in with our life skills workshops though, some other skill that they're doing.

06:38.020 --> 06:42.980
So, you know, with an acting workshop, it's obviously public speaking is one of the things.

06:42.980 --> 06:48.500
It may be building something out, writing their own play, writing their own music, things like that.

06:49.220 --> 06:50.260
Oh, and you know what?

06:50.260 --> 06:54.100
It turns out I just looked at my iPad and the next question was, do you do acting?

06:54.100 --> 06:55.220
Yeah, we do acting.

06:55.220 --> 07:01.940
In fact, I will tell you yesterday was the anniversary of my oldest daughter's debut

07:01.940 --> 07:05.860
as the lead Annie in one of the plays that we did.

07:05.860 --> 07:10.980
And it was back in 2015 and it was so cute.

07:10.980 --> 07:12.100
Here's an interesting question.

07:12.100 --> 07:16.340
I get a lot of people wondering about how we're going to expand our education system.

07:16.340 --> 07:20.980
And this question is, do you think that your education system would work in any country?

07:21.780 --> 07:26.100
The short answer is yes, I do believe it could work in any country.

07:26.100 --> 07:32.100
The longer answer is there's got to be philosophical alignment with a couple of key

07:32.100 --> 07:33.860
points around our model.

07:33.860 --> 07:41.940
First of all, the idea that we do not use teachers to teach academic content to students

07:41.940 --> 07:44.260
in a teacher in front of a classroom model.

07:44.260 --> 07:48.420
And that is something that just feels so hard for people to get their heads around

07:48.420 --> 07:54.260
because we all grew up in that system and we've always been told like a great teacher

07:54.260 --> 07:56.900
is the key to learning something.

07:56.900 --> 08:02.420
So you have to believe that now we believe a great teacher is key to our success as well.

08:02.420 --> 08:05.940
The difference is they're focusing on motivation and emotional support,

08:05.940 --> 08:08.420
not on conveying academic content.

08:08.420 --> 08:09.540
So that's one of the big things.

08:09.540 --> 08:15.540
The other big philosophy that you have to be okay with is the idea that it only takes

08:15.540 --> 08:20.100
a couple of hours to do the academic content when you do it in our model.

08:20.100 --> 08:25.380
And so you have to be willing to allow the rest of the day to be done differently.

08:25.380 --> 08:30.180
And so I've had conversations with school leaders from all over the United States

08:30.180 --> 08:35.620
and all over the world who say, wow, we'd love to take your two-hour learning program

08:35.620 --> 08:36.980
and use that in the morning.

08:36.980 --> 08:41.700
And then the rest of school day will still do more math, science, reading, language,

08:41.700 --> 08:44.340
because that's just what they believe is developed.

08:44.340 --> 08:48.260
For us, what we're doing is we're giving kids our most valuable resource,

08:48.260 --> 08:52.580
which is time back to go do all these other cool things and develop life skills.

08:52.580 --> 08:55.540
We're not trying to cram in more academic time.

08:55.540 --> 08:58.580
And that's something that just from a philosophy perspective,

08:59.140 --> 09:02.260
we have to do another kind of interesting thing around countries.

09:02.260 --> 09:05.380
So we've done a program in Malawi with refugee students.

09:05.380 --> 09:08.980
We've done a program in Eastern Europe with Ukrainian refugee students.

09:09.700 --> 09:15.860
So we have had this type of model work with great success in these other countries.

09:16.420 --> 09:20.740
And they've implemented so many of the motivation models that we use at Alpha.

09:20.740 --> 09:25.380
Obviously, though, we do need internet, you need computers, those types of things.

09:25.380 --> 09:31.620
I also got a few questions from you around the whole idea of college and how do we prepare kids

09:31.620 --> 09:33.140
to be successful in college.

09:33.140 --> 09:36.900
And we should actually do a totally separate podcast around college.

09:36.900 --> 09:42.100
And the philosophy that Alpha has around how our kids are getting into top tier universities.

09:42.100 --> 09:46.500
In fact, we just had two early acceptances to Stanford University, my alma mater.

09:47.620 --> 09:48.740
Pretty exciting go card.

09:49.300 --> 09:50.420
So that was fun to see.

09:51.060 --> 09:54.180
But here's the question that I wanted to address was,

09:54.180 --> 10:01.540
do extracurriculars make up for average academics when it comes to going to college?

10:01.540 --> 10:06.660
And I think one of the things that I noticed parents have is this very ingrained belief

10:07.140 --> 10:12.900
that in order to get into college these days, you have to have perfect grades and have taken

10:12.900 --> 10:19.700
as many AP courses as possible and have high SATs and just really, really focus on the academic

10:19.700 --> 10:20.500
part of it.

10:20.500 --> 10:26.580
And here's the thing, especially in top 20 universities, all of that academic stuff

10:27.220 --> 10:28.900
is table stakes now.

10:29.460 --> 10:32.580
Like lots of kids have taken a bunch of APs.

10:32.580 --> 10:36.420
Lots of kids are able to get great scores on their SATs.

10:36.420 --> 10:41.780
And so while it's important and what you need to be able to do is show that you have the ability

10:41.780 --> 10:46.100
to handle the academic rigor of a university by having that.

10:46.100 --> 10:50.340
The key thing is to really stand out in some other way.

10:50.340 --> 10:53.780
And that's often through extracurricular activities.

10:53.780 --> 10:57.620
Now extracurricular activities aren't the same as they used to be either.

10:57.620 --> 11:03.780
Back when I was in school and being the captain of the debate team or on the varsity tennis team,

11:03.780 --> 11:05.620
you know, those were the things we wanted.

11:05.620 --> 11:10.660
I think what universities are really wanting to see are the kinds of things that our students are

11:10.660 --> 11:11.940
able to do at Alpha.

11:11.940 --> 11:16.980
Something that's very unique, something where they've really taken an interest or a passion that

11:16.980 --> 11:21.940
they have and they've gone and become experts and done something big with it and made an impact.

11:21.940 --> 11:26.660
I also know, and I talked to university admissions people on a regular basis,

11:26.660 --> 11:32.500
they want to know how you as a student are going to impact the school's community.

11:32.500 --> 11:34.020
And so those are the things to think of.

11:34.900 --> 11:37.940
Last piece of advice that I'm going to give to parents listening to this,

11:37.940 --> 11:39.780
especially at the high school level.

11:39.780 --> 11:45.060
You cannot force your kids to do what you think is what they should be doing.

11:45.060 --> 11:48.260
Find the thing that they're excited about, that they're passionate about,

11:48.260 --> 11:50.660
and encourage them to go big.

11:50.660 --> 11:53.380
Now you can still have a high standard of excellence for it,

11:53.380 --> 11:57.540
and you can give them support for this, but you cannot make your kid go do things.

11:57.540 --> 12:01.220
I am on a college admissions Facebook page,

12:01.220 --> 12:07.140
and I'm amazed at how many parents are literally trying to live their children's life for them

12:07.140 --> 12:10.740
very blatantly against their children's even wishes.

12:10.740 --> 12:13.620
And please stop doing that if you're one of those parents.

12:13.620 --> 12:14.580
Don't do that.

12:14.580 --> 12:19.620
Instead, help your kid find the thing that they love and help them develop

12:19.620 --> 12:23.060
the desire to be self-driven because they're excited about their passion.

12:23.060 --> 12:25.540
Again, you can still have high standards for them,

12:25.540 --> 12:27.780
but help them go find the thing they love.

12:27.780 --> 12:32.340
So if you're a control freak, which I am too, by the way,

12:32.340 --> 12:35.460
channel that energy instead of saying like, you must do this,

12:35.460 --> 12:39.380
channel that energy into helping them find the thing that they're excited about and love.

12:39.380 --> 12:41.060
And it may take a few tries.

12:41.060 --> 12:42.020
It may take things.

12:42.020 --> 12:43.380
My daughter's a great example.

12:43.380 --> 12:48.580
My youngest daughter, she used social media as her main extracurricular.

12:48.580 --> 12:51.220
What person in the world would think, oh, I know.

12:51.220 --> 12:54.020
I think my daughter should just spend all her time on TikTok.

12:54.020 --> 12:59.220
Well, 2.3 million followers later and a lot of success.

12:59.220 --> 13:03.540
It turned out that she was able to channel this interest she had in this past time

13:03.540 --> 13:06.820
into something really, really helpful and really valuable.

13:06.820 --> 13:09.540
Okay, thank you so much for so many of the questions that you got.

13:09.540 --> 13:10.260
This was really fun.

13:10.260 --> 13:14.100
I loved watching these come in on my stories when I posted this on Instagram.

13:14.100 --> 13:16.500
And feel free to keep them coming too.

13:16.500 --> 13:19.460
We love getting to read the messages that you send.

13:19.460 --> 13:21.380
And we'll do another one of these if you guys liked it.

13:21.380 --> 13:22.100
So have a great one.

